      "message": "this is a trick - it checks if the function return type isn\u0027t the same as the function type. It\u0027s next to impossible to make this happen (function to return itself), so is_same\u003c\u003e here is a placeholder for |true|. The only reason why it\u0027s used is to make use of SFINAE - if the thing isn\u0027t callable with the supplied arguments the whole expression doesn\u0027t compile, so it gets eliminated and is_callable_with_args uses the first specialization to return |false|",
